---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
import FindingCard from '@/components/FindingCard.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="Impact Whey Protein Milkshake — Myprotein PDP">

  <section class="report-intro">
    <h1 class="report-h1">UX Audit: Impact Whey Protein Milkshake</h1>
    <p class="report-meta">Myprotein PDP &mdash; Audited 1 June 2026</p>
    <p class="report-summary">
      This audit covers the product detail page for the Impact Whey Protein Milkshake range on
      Myprotein. Ten findings are documented across desktop and mobile viewports, spanning
      information architecture, visual design, accessibility, and conversion friction.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="findings-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Findings</h2>

    <!-- HIGH PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard title="Variant selector overwhelm — 88 flavours shown with no filtering" viewport="Both" priority="high">
      <p slot="what">
        The flavour dropdown lists all 88 variants in a single unscrolled list. There is no search
        field, no grouping, and no way to surface popular or new options first.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Choice overload is a well-documented conversion barrier (Iyengar &amp; Lepper, 2000).
        Users forced to scan 88 options are more likely to abandon than choose.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add a text-filter input at the top of the dropdown. Surface the top 6–8 bestseller
        flavours by default with a "Show all" expansion. Consider a visual swatch grid for
        flavours with distinct colour associations.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard title="Add-to-bag CTA is below the fold on mobile at default font size" viewport="Mobile" priority="high">
      <p slot="what">
        On a 390 px viewport at the default 16 px browser font, the primary
        <code>Add to Bag</code> button does not appear until the user scrolls past the image
        carousel, price block, and the full variant selector.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The primary conversion action must be visible without scrolling on mobile. Every extra
        scroll reduces the likelihood of a tap.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Introduce a sticky bottom bar on mobile containing the price, selected variant summary,
        and the Add to Bag CTA. This pattern is used by Amazon, ASOS, and Nike mobile PDPs.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- MEDIUM PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard title="Nutrition table is collapsed by default with no teaser content" viewport="Both" priority="medium">
      <p slot="what">
        The full nutrition panel is hidden behind an accordion. No macros or serving-size data
        are shown in the collapsed state — users see only the label "Nutritional Information".
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        For a protein supplement, macros (protein per serving, calories, carbs) are primary
        purchase signals. Hiding them creates an extra tap barrier at a critical decision point.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Show protein per serving, calories, and carbs inline on the card in the collapsed state.
        The accordion can still exist for the full table, but the headline numbers should be
        scannable immediately.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard title="Flavour-specific images are not loaded — all variants show the same pack shot" viewport="Both" priority="medium">
      <p slot="what">
        Selecting a flavour such as "Salted Caramel" does not update the product image. The
        same Chocolate Smooth bag is shown for every selection.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Flavour-matched imagery reduces purchase uncertainty and builds confidence. Showing the
        wrong pack colour increases post-purchase disappointment and potential returns.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Map flavour variant IDs to their corresponding image assets. Where flavour-specific
        photography is unavailable, show a colour-tinted placeholder that matches the expected
        packaging colour.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard title="Subscription saving is buried in a secondary tab with no inline signpost" viewport="Both" priority="medium">
      <p slot="what">
        The subscribe-and-save option (typically 20% off) lives in a tab below the main
        purchase block. First-time visitors see only the one-off price with no prompt that a
        recurring saving exists.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Subscription revenue is higher LTV. If users never discover the option it cannot
        convert. A visible saving anchor also makes the one-off price feel less competitive.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add a small callout pill adjacent to the price — e.g. "Subscribe &amp; save 20%" — that
        scrolls to or expands the subscription section when tapped.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard title="Review score shown but review count is not linked to the review panel" viewport="Desktop" priority="medium">
      <p slot="what">
        The star rating and aggregate score (e.g. 4.6/5) appear near the title, but clicking
        them does not anchor-scroll to the reviews section further down the page.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Social proof is a key trust signal. Users who want to validate the score should be able
        to reach the reviews in one click. A dead star rating is a missed engagement hook.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Wrap the rating block in an anchor tag pointing to <code>#reviews</code>. Ensure the
        reviews section has that corresponding <code>id</code> attribute.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard title="Size selector defaults to 1 kg but 2.5 kg is the bestseller — no bestseller label" viewport="Both" priority="medium">
      <p slot="what">
        The size selector opens on the 1 kg option. The 2.5 kg SKU reportedly drives the
        majority of volume but carries no visual differentiator (no "Best Value" or "Most
        Popular" badge).
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Defaulting to the wrong size creates friction for returning customers and misses an
        opportunity to anchor users toward higher-AOV SKUs.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Default the size selector to the bestselling SKU. Add a "Best Value" or "Most Popular"
        label to that option within the selector.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- LOW PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard title="Page title tag does not include the flavour variant or size" viewport="Both" priority="low">
      <p slot="what">
        The <code>&lt;title&gt;</code> element reads "Impact Whey Protein | Myprotein" regardless
        of which variant is selected. Size and flavour parameters are not reflected.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Specific titles improve CTR from search results pages and make browser tabs identifiable
        when multiple Myprotein tabs are open.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Update the title dynamically on variant selection via JavaScript, or generate
        variant-specific URLs with server-rendered titles for the most common combinations.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard title="Trust badges (Informed Sport, Banned Substance tested) are below the fold on desktop" viewport="Desktop" priority="low">
      <p slot="what">
        Third-party certification logos appear in the page footer area, well below the purchase
        block. They are not visible at the point of decision.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        For sports nutrition, third-party testing certifications directly address a buyer
        anxiety (contamination risk for competitive athletes). Placing them near the CTA
        increases their conversion impact.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Move a compact version of the trust badges (icon + name only) to the area immediately
        below the Add to Bag button.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard title="Breadcrumb trail truncates on mobile, showing only the current page name" viewport="Mobile" priority="low">
      <p slot="what">
        On viewports below 430 px the breadcrumb collapses to just the current page name with
        no back-navigation affordance.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Users who navigate deep from a category page lose orientation context. A single-level
        back link ("← Protein Powders") would restore this without consuming space.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Replace the truncated breadcrumb with a single "← {parent category}" link on mobile,
        matching the pattern used in the report header.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Design Consistency</h2>
    <p>
      The page mixes two generations of the Myprotein design system. The image carousel and
      review section use the newer component library (rounded corners, Figtree/brand font stack,
      teal accents), while the variant selector and nutrition accordion retain older flat-UI
      styling with sharp corners and a different grey palette. Unifying these components would
      reduce visual noise and improve perceived quality.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Accessibility Notes</h2>
    <p>
      The flavour dropdown passes basic keyboard navigation. However, the image carousel
      auto-advances without user input and has no visible pause control, which fails WCAG 2.1
      SC 2.2.2 (Pause, Stop, Hide). Additionally, the star rating SVG icons carry no
      <code>aria-label</code> — screen readers announce the score as an unlabelled graphic.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Conversion Summary</h2>
    <p>
      The two high-priority findings (variant overwhelm and below-fold CTA on mobile) are the
      most likely sources of measurable drop-off in the current funnel. Addressing those two
      items alone could be expected to move add-to-bag rate on mobile meaningfully, based on
      comparable interventions on similar nutrition PDPs. The five medium-priority findings
      represent secondary optimisation opportunities that are lower effort but would compound
      the improvement.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Recommended Implementation Order</h2>
    <ol class="recommendations">
      <li>Sticky bottom CTA bar on mobile (high impact, self-contained CSS/JS change)</li>
      <li>Variant selector — add text filter and default bestseller pre-selection</li>
      <li>Subscription save callout pill adjacent to price</li>
      <li>Inline macro summary in collapsed nutrition accordion state</li>
      <li>Trust badges moved to below-CTA position</li>
      <li>Review score linked to reviews section anchor</li>
      <li>Flavour-matched imagery (dependent on asset availability)</li>
      <li>Dynamic page title per variant (SEO value compounds over time)</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style is:global>
  .finding-card code {
    font-family: Menlo, Monaco, 'Courier New', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    padding: 1px 5px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
  }
</style>

<style>
  .report-intro {
    margin-bottom: 40px;
  }

  .report-h1 {
    font-size: 26px;
    font-weight: 800;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    line-height: 1.25;
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }

  .report-meta {
    font-size: 13px;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    opacity: 0.65;
    margin-bottom: 14px;
  }

  .report-summary {
    font-size: 15px;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    max-width: 680px;
  }

  .findings-section {
    margin-bottom: 48px;
  }

  .section-heading {
    font-size: 18px;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 20px;
    padding-bottom: 10px;
    border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1);
  }

  .prose-section {
    margin-bottom: 36px;
  }

  .prose-section p {
    font-size: 15px;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
  }

  .prose-section code {
    font-family: Menlo, Monaco, 'Courier New', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    padding: 1px 5px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
  }

  .recommendations {
    padding-left: 20px;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 10px;
  }

  .recommendations li {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
  }
</style>
